 {"id":"bd-3pc3p","title":"[PROVIDER-OPENROUTER-DYNAMIC-MODELS] Handle OpenRouter dynamic model registry","description":"## Problem

OpenRouter is fundamentally different from the other 4 new providers (Groq, Cerebras, Kimi, Qwen). It is a **proxy/aggregator** that routes to upstream providers. Its model registry is:
- **Dynamic**: Models are added/removed as upstream providers change
- **Large**: Potentially thousands of models across all upstream providers
- **Heterogeneous**: Models have different capabilities, pricing, and context windows
- **Namespaced**: Model IDs use `provider/model-name` format (e.g., `anthropic/claude-3-opus`)

The current pi_agent architecture assumes a static model registry defined at build time in models.json. This does not work for OpenRouter.

## Design Decision Required

### Option A: Static Snapshot
- Hardcode the top N most popular OpenRouter models in models.json
- Periodically update the list (e.g., monthly)
- Simple but incomplete — users cannot access new models without a release

### Option B: API-Fetched Model List
- On first use (or periodic refresh), call `GET https://openrouter.ai/api/v1/models`
- Cache the response locally (e.g., ~/.pi/cache/openrouter_models.json)
- Resolve models dynamically from cache
- More complex but complete — users always have access to current models

### Option C: Hybrid (Recommended)
- Ship a curated default list (top 20-30 models) in models.json
- Allow API fetch as an optional enhancement (behind --refresh-models flag)
- Any model ID matching the `provider/model-name` pattern auto-routes to OpenRouter
- Cache fetched list with 24h TTL

### OpenRouter-Specific Considerations
- **HTTP-Referer header**: Required by OpenRouter TOS for API calls
- **Pricing**: Different models have different per-token costs; should be visible in model selection
- **Fallback routing**: OpenRouter can auto-select a model if `openrouter/auto` is specified
- **Context window**: Varies dramatically by model (4K to 200K+)
- **Rate limits**: Per-model rate limits from upstream, plus OpenRouter-level limits

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Design decision documented (Option A/B/C)
- [ ] If Option B or C: API fetch + cache implementation specified
- [ ] Model resolver handles `provider/model-name` format
- [ ] HTTP-Referer header included in all OpenRouter requests
- [ ] Pricing metadata available in model selection (if fetched)
- [ ] Stale cache handling (TTL expiry, forced refresh)
- [ ] Unit tests for model name parsing and routing

## Dependencies
- Depends on PROVIDER-OPENROUTER-SPEC (bd-3uqg.11.7.1)
- Blocks PROVIDER-OPENROUTER-MODELS (bd-3uqg.11.7.4)","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","assignee":"codex","created_at":"2026-02-13T05:47:57.776639276Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-02-13T09:42:25.181254218Z","closed_at":"2026-02-13T09:42:25.181224052Z","close_reason":"Completed: Option-C dynamic model contract, provider/model resolver hardening, OpenRouter attribution header defaults, and targeted tests.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-3pc3p","depends_on_id":"bd-3uqg.11.7.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-07T03:28:01Z","created_by":"import"}]}
 {"id":"bd-3pcw","title":"Task: Add property-based tests for extension runtime","description":"# Task: Add Property-Based Tests for Extension Runtime

## Objective

Use proptest to verify invariants hold for all inputs, catching edge cases not covered by fixtures.

## Background

Property-based testing generates random inputs and verifies properties hold. This catches edge cases that manual test cases miss.

## Properties to Test

### 1. Hostcall Never Panics

No matter what input, hostcalls should return Ok or Err, never panic.

```rust
proptest\! {
    #[test]
    fn hostcall_never_panics(
        hostcall_type in "(tool|exec|http|session|ui|events)",
        method in "[a-z]{1,20}",
        args in any::<serde_json::Value>(),
    ) {
        let runtime = create_test_runtime_sync();
        let request = HostcallRequest {
            hostcall_type,
            method,
            args,
        };

        // Should not panic
        let _ = runtime.dispatch_hostcall_sync(request);
    }
}
```

### 2. Invalid Type Returns Error

Unknown hostcall types always return an error.

```rust
proptest\! {
    #[test]
    fn invalid_type_returns_error(
        invalid_type in "[a-z]{1,20}".prop_filter("known types", |s| {
            \!["tool", "exec", "http", "session", "ui", "events"].contains(&s.as_str())
        }),
        method in "[a-z]{1,20}",
    ) {
        let runtime = create_test_runtime_sync();
        let request = HostcallRequest {
            hostcall_type: invalid_type,
            method,
            args: json\!({}),
        };

        let result = runtime.dispatch_hostcall_sync(request);
        prop_assert\!(result.is_err());
    }
}
```

### 3. Missing Required Fields Return Error

Hostcalls with missing required fields return appropriate errors.

```rust
proptest\! {
    #[test]
    fn tool_register_requires_name(
        description in "[a-z ]{0,100}",
    ) {
        let runtime = create_test_runtime_sync();
        let request = HostcallRequest {
            hostcall_type: "tool".into(),
            method: "register".into(),
            args: json\!({
                "description": description,
                // name is missing
            }),
        };

        let result = runtime.dispatch_hostcall_sync(request);
        prop_assert\!(result.is_err());
    }
}
```

### 4. State Consistency

Multiple operations don't corrupt state.

```rust
proptest\! {
    #[test]
    fn repeated_operations_consistent(
        ops in prop::collection::vec(any::<HostcallOp>(), 1..20),
    ) {
        let runtime = create_test_runtime_sync();

        for op in ops {
            let _ = runtime.dispatch_hostcall_sync(op.to_request());
        }

        // Runtime should still be usable
        let status = runtime.health_check();
        prop_assert\!(status.is_ok());
    }
}
```

### 5. Unicode Handling

Unicode strings don't cause issues.

```rust
proptest\! {
    #[test]
    fn unicode_strings_handled(
        message in ".*",  // Any unicode string
    ) {
        let runtime = create_test_runtime_sync();

        // Show spinner with unicode
        let result = runtime.dispatch_hostcall_sync(HostcallRequest {
            hostcall_type: "ui".into(),
            method: "showSpinner".into(),
            args: json\!({ "message": message }),
        });

        // Should succeed or return recoverable error
        if let Ok(response) = result {
